# Setting Up Git and GitHub â€“ **Diaz, Zianne P.**

This guide provides step-by-step instructions on how to set up Git and GitHub, including basic operations such as `git init`, `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`, and other essential commands.

---

## ğŸ“¦ 1. Installing Visual Studio Code

- Download VS Code from the [official website](https://code.visualstudio.com/)
- Choose the correct version for your OS (Windows/Mac)
- Run the installer and click **Next** until finished
- VS Code should now be installed on your system

---

## ğŸ”§ 2. Installing Git

- Visit [git-scm.com](https://git-scm.com/)
- Download Git for your OS (Windows, Mac, Linux)
- For Windows, choose the **64-bit Standalone Installer**
- Click **Next** repeatedly until Git installs
- Confirm installation by right-clicking any folder:
  - You should see **Git Bash Here**
  - If not, try reinstalling Git

---

## ğŸ“ 3. Setting Up the Project Folder

- Create a new folder for your project
- Name it following this format:  
  **SurnameFirstName_DSA_Midterms**  
  _Example: `DiazZianne_DSA_Midterms`_

---

## âœ… 4. Verifying Installations

- Open Start menu or Finder and search **Visual Studio Code**
- Right-click your folder and confirm you see **Git Bash Here**
- If not visible, reinstall Git

---

## ğŸ’» 5. Opening the Folder in VS Code

1. Open the project folder in File Explorer or Finder
2. Click the address bar and type:
   ```bash
   cmd
   ```
3. In Command Prompt, launch VS Code with:
   ```bash
   code .
   ```

---

## âš™ï¸ 6. Configuring VS Code Terminal

- In VS Code, open terminal:  
  **View > Terminal** or press `Ctrl + \` (backtick)
- Switch terminal to **Command Prompt (CMD)** using dropdown

---

## ğŸ’¾ 7. Enabling Auto Save

- Go to **File > Auto Save**
- Ensure it is checked âœ…

---

## ğŸ§© 8. Installing VS Code Extensions

Install the following:

- âœ… **Conventional Commits**
- âœ… **Source Control** (usually installed by default)

Then:

- Click the **Accounts** icon in VS Code
- Sign in with your GitHub account

---

## ğŸ“ 9. Creating Your First File

1. Right-click in Explorer pane
2. Click **New File**
3. Name it:
   ```
   hello_world.html
   ```
4. Add sample HTML:
   ```html
   <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
   ```

---

## ğŸ™ 10. Creating a GitHub Repository

1. Go to [GitHub](https://github.com)
2. Click **New Repository**
3. Repository name:  
   ```
   DSA_Midterm
   ```
4. Set visibility: **Public**
5. **Do NOT check** "Add README"
6. Click **Create Repository**

---

## ğŸ”„ 11. Initializing Git in Your Folder

Open **Git Bash** inside your project folder:

```bash
git init
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"
```

---

## ğŸ§· 12. Adding and Committing Files

1. Create a file called:
   ```
   README.md
   ```
2. In Git Bash:
   ```bash
   git add README.md
   git commit -m "Initial commit"
   ```

---

## ğŸŒ 13. Connecting to GitHub

1. Copy your GitHub repo URL (ends in `.git`)
2. In Git Bash:
   ```bash
   git branch -M main
   git remote add origin https://github.com/YourUsername/DSA_Midterm.git
   git push -u origin main
   ```

---

## ğŸ” 14. Uploading Changes with VS Code

1. Make changes (e.g., edit files or add new ones)
2. Go to **Source Control** panel in VS Code
3. Click â• to **Stage Changes**
4. Click **Conventional Commits**
5. Select:
   - Type: `feat` or `fix`
   - Scope (optional)
   - Description: `added hello world`
6. Click âœ… or **Sync Changes**

---

## ğŸ§ª 15. Example Update

1. Add:
   ```
   page1.html
   ```
2. Modify:
   ```
   hello_world.html
   ```
   Change "Hello World" â†’ "Hello Universe"
3. Commit message:
   - Type: `fix`
   - Message: `Fixed Hello World and added Page 1`

---

## ğŸŒ 16. Why GitHub Is Important

- You can **clone** your repository anywhere using:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YourUsername/DSA_Midterm.git
```

- Work from any computer, just `clone`, then `code .`

---

## ğŸ§¾ 17. Updating README.md

- Your `README.md` explains your project
- Add info like:
  ```markdown
  # DSA Midterm
  My midterm project for Data Structures and Algorithms
  ```
- Then stage, commit, and push:
  ```bash
  git add README.md
  git commit -m "Updated README"
  git push
  ```

---

## ğŸ§µ 18. Markdown Basics

Here are some Markdown examples for your README:

```markdown
